document.title: CW Middle School American History Grade Levels. Course. Theme. Strand. Expectation

E23A0526CA8F4892A02A44F898F133AE.description: Trace the development of African American culture in nonslave states and in the context of slavery.

5C950120B836470697D20B382CD5780A.description:
Analyze the evolution of the Abolitionist Movement to trace
its continued development and evaluate its impact.

A543EF532583498698F5FBFF7248A555.description:
Analyze the evolution of the women’s movementto trace its
continued development and evaluate its impact.

A8BB1B57CD7A4217B72A42B6D0AD6D76.description:
Describe the impact of scientific and technological advances on
the outcome of the war and its effect on people and diverse
groups.

6A4F877616EF47828A5EA4D23C2ACDA2.description:
Determine the impact of the ideas contained in major speeches,
literature, music, and writings from diverse individuals on the
perspectives of American people, groups and movements.

F2600CE8548A48369E2D3D95590F0C6B.description:
Analyze patterns of immigration to determine their impacts on
the cultural, social, political and economic development.

D8E52E3CFDFB49F5AC6761BD942F51E6.description:
Describe the culture and accomplishments of native
American cultures to compare the various ways they responded
to American expansion.

4746A7E310D74F7C996E5D377569AA73.description:
Analyze artistic, intellectual, and religious movements to show
how they reflect the aspirations and beliefs of the developing
nation.

3BD010E2222A4477871C50265FB238BF.description:
Analyze the experiences of enslaved peoples in North and
South America to determine the cultural impact and enduring
consequences.

C7B3F9C697FD43309BF54E315B416826.description:
Evaluate the effectiveness of various reform movements, laws, and
events to determine their impact on the promise of American
ideals.

C2673BD54DEB450EA6FBA57D1BE600E0.description:
Analyze the artistic and intellectual achievements of early
Americans to provide evidence of an emerging American identity

2F82D5D381C0424983408D2FEDE18CA1.description:
Evaluate laws, events, and perspectives to determine the
extent to which individuals and groups could participate in, and
realize, the promise of American ideals.

C49870B9CF5F4F4FACE3CB1B49D47013.description:
Compare and contrast the perspectives of individuals and
groups regarding the development of the American
governmental system to explain emerging divisions and
political philosophies.

314DFBA1F45643E9AB632EB9570CDF03.description:
Analyze populations of colonies/states to explain how their
cultural, religious, social, and economic characteristics
influenced the emergence of regional identity.

0C1801689A5A433AB9D641E5FF460F84.description:
Analyze the perspectives of diverse individuals and groups to
explain the extent of their support for the RevolutionaryWar.

D34F162FC6F44024B12FCD0AF42BC187.description:
Compare and contrast the interaction of European settlers with Native
Americans in both North and South America.

FE0712B3FB584AA6AD9D3EC9299CCCB2.description:
Analyze the religious, cultural, and intellectual developments
of the European colonies to explain the development of
regionalism and an American identity.

026D911F9A3B4287AA74D11FA4A3A445.description:
Analyze the religious, cultural, political and intellectual
developments of Spanish, Portuguese, British and French regions
to explain the development of diverse cultures throughout the
Americas.

9B75E96D506840C2A79E797442A0D230.description:
Using an American history lens, examine the origins and
impact of social structures and stratification on societies and
relationships between peoples.

FDF63B0704F84A3281E911039EF058C3.description:
Using an American history lens, describe how peoples’
perspectives shaped the sources/artifacts they created.

0BE4ED74C71B4B11861FB16E67973971.description:
Compare the economic strengths and weaknesses of the North
and South before, during and immediately after the Civil War.

AE0287DB9DAF4A0792FF675850530DBF.description:
Explain how the expansion of industrialization, transportation,
and technological developments influenced different regions and
the relationship among those regions.

8C2BBBD2CAA24DCC83E84F8F6EA7FBA6.description:
Trace the continued development of the American economic
system to explain how taxes, tariffs, and monetary policies were
used to establish sustainability and growth.

F9F699FFE38A494FA0F731033CBDB832.description:
Explain how the expansion of industrialization,
transportation and technological developments influenced
different regions and the relationship among those regions.

B5FAEA6E21D54AC08B462608019BABB4.description:
Analyze the origins and characteristics of coercive labor
systems, including slavery, and their impact on economic and
political expansion.

32B77F6AF231400BA6ED3C1C393C2563.description:
Trace the development of the American economic system to
explain how taxes, tariffs, and monetary policies were used to
establish sustainability and growth.

A3F3C4F0A9CA4DF2AF7288662C17E2A3.description:
Compare the emerging economic characteristics of the nation
and colonial regions to make predictions about future
expansion and conflict.

42D9F4C9D6DB49FEA5C48258C48F14CF.description:
Describe the function and purpose of taxes imposed by Great
Britain following the Seven Years War, evaluating colonial
responses to them.

645C3EF1CDBF49C29EE990CAC314A962.description:
Analyze the mercantile system to explain colonial responses to
economic control by European nations including Great Britain.

17BC91A9DA9649EAB792ACF4F345D659.description:
Compare sources of labor, emerging economic production,
and availability of land in the New World and their impact on
economic development in North and South America.

B1CD0E1F60B148B3958E5727C2E46AA4.description:
Using an American history lens, examine the opportunity costs
and benefits of economic decisions on society as a whole as well
as on individuals, prior to c. 1870.

1D40047FCB674945BD2B061033899136.description:
Compare major patterns of population distribution,
demographics and migrations in the United States and the impact
of those patterns on cultures and community life.

C66017FE602D4FF6A4CE69FD10BD24F1.description:
Evaluate the significance of geography on the conduct of the
war and strategy of the North and South.

A5F1D3B2AC4548B1B5E6EDA42496C2D1.description:
Analyze the United States’ geography of North, South, and West
in order to explain their regional cultural, social and economic
differences.

ACC9E9A0CFE34109ACBE1EB36E492440.description:
Compare major patterns of population distribution,
demographics and migrations in the United States and the impact
of those patterns on cultures and community life c. 1812-1848.

EDA3A78FFC5B4CCCBE55714E544A3184.description:
Assess Manifest Destiny in relation to push-pull factors,
geographic features, and human environmental interactions
to determine their influence on the movement of goods,
people and ideas.

CCAD242C45544ECF8B36556A23FCBCA5.description:
Trace the changing boundaries of the United States and
describe how it represents the changing relationships with its
neighbors and Native Americans.

FC2803BCBC7B41A1BFB6838F8A049521.description:
Compare major patterns of population distribution,
demographics and migrations in the United States during this era
c. 1763-1812.

E6CEDB86F15341D1B103404F064ED816.description:
Evaluate the relationships among population, representation,
and their effect on power in the new government.

0F79F502FA804D248BF01B7E3005F56C.description:
Draw conclusions about regional conflict and cooperation as a
consequence of physical geography.

C64A1FF6B07D4D2CBC78437106917A75.description:
Compare major patterns of population distribution,
demographics and migrations in the United States and the impact
of those patterns on cultures and community life.

B19941004B104F4088E74846227A7561.description:
Analyze the geography of colonial regions to explain their
cultural, social and economicdifferences.

300B8FDB3AE5452993ABFADE48387D53.description:
Analyze diverseNative American cultures in North, Central
and South America to explain the way they adapted to their
various environments.

1D4091B7B6E946B2A2986EAA40155E14.description:
Locate major cities of Missouri, the United States, and the
world; states of the United States and key world nations; the
world’s continents, and oceans; and major topographical features
of the United States.

D9485783E2EA4D2EB6DEEFC2B909E1AB.description:
Explain how the physical and human characteristics of regions
in the Americas prior to c. 1870 are connected to changing
identity and culture.

A1306415437D4B3A8A2E0A61F8CB9CEF.description:
Create and use maps and other graphic representations in
order to explain relationships and reveal patterns or trends in
American history prior to c. 1870.

0849D800782546DE9428B776F8B4D494.description:
Compare and contrast the governmental systems of the US
North and South to determine the strengths and weaknesses of
federal and confederal systems.

DCAAE279EB6F43F88B474663B6F5FE04.description:
Analyze the election of 1860 to explain the development of
political parties and how they influence the selection of leaders.

5B2E25B55E704248A6F313854DC0ED25.description:
Analyze federalism and popular sovereignty to explain
peoples’ expectations of the role of government and their place in
governance.

1657F137DB1446DD9B23B01E97CD4421.description:
Compare responses of government systems in the North
and South to major legislation, executive orders, and court
decisions before, during and immediately after the Civil War.

7EB99B96778642789B37C6099AC631BB.description:
Explain how the principles of rule of law, separation of powers,
checks and balance, and federalism were impacted by Jacksonian
democracy.

CCE4F307FB26402DBEDB226B247E9619.description:
Analyze landmark Supreme Court cases to determine the effect
on the definition and expansion of federal power.

FE81FB600DA64FADB408883C63318469.description:
Trace the expansion of voting rights and patterns and explain
how it impacted elections and political movements.

940376E8606D4E608C1F82C6F2B09B22.description:
Examine elections, issues, laws, and events of this time period
to explain how the concepts of judicial review, elastic clause, and
an amendment process were established or used to meet
challenges.

647F29D1ECF44203A7B174E833E535D6.description:
Describe the origins and purposes of the Bill of Rights and
evaluate the enduring significance of these concepts to the
preservation of individual rights and liberties.

9310DBDC6D234F7BBFB100BF3306C50C.description:
Apply the principles of rule of law, representation, separation
of powers, checks and balances, and federalism to explain the
purposes and functions of the Constitution.

80B45BA887CE4174A3C26DE6A500D478.description:
Evaluate the successes and challenges of the Articles of
Confederation to explain the need for a Constitutional
Convention.

83976022C93B42DDA032FB5F3A28ADA4.description:
Apply the principles of inalienable rights, popular sovereignty,
natural rights, and social contract to evaluate the purpose and
legacy of the Declaration of Independence

26C10BD05A7141CAB71F9782CA1325A3.description:
Apply the concept of representation to the conflict between the
colonies and Great Britain.

A7E163634FDD48D186563CFCC08EBCE1.description:
Evaluate the impact of the French and Indian Wars on Great
Britain’s approach to colonial rule.

E89765B7B64F4509B140B86A90294D80.description:
Analyze local and colonial governments to trace the factors
influencing their structure and function.

875847FC13864639ABAFF7DE10EBFA55.description:
Explain how the founding of English colonies influenced their
governments and expectations for self-rule

9B4B19546B1A40F6B570A7E8331C16C2.description:
Compare the governmental systems of European powers to
determine their effect on colonization in the Americas.

109CCC40CD4E419F8B7BA417D38960FE.description:
Analyze laws, policies, and processes to determine how
governmental systems affectindividuals and groups in society in
American history prior to c. 1870.

F2F9C8D271764AE1ACA71E551C8C88AC.description:
Describe critical developments and turning points in the Civil
War, including major battles.

9662430CE83E4419AAA1D2AE47C403F8.description:
Trace the events as well as political, cultural, economic, and
social conditions leading to conflict between Northern and
Southern states.

0623C8FE610042F0A30C23793C9FEC7C.description:
Analyze political compromises over slavery in the territories to
explain intensifying sectional conflicts

A3FF22FA66E944888BB0B700B3681E0A.description:
Analyze the forced removal and resettlements of Native
Americans to determine its impact on their cultures and
civilization.

C23CF6304CFB466DA04D6DDC90458E76.description:
Evaluate the responses of North and South American leaders to
the social, political, economic and religious challenges of the
period.

8336891E495A4881B9AF9BF2E573EAA0.description:
Analyze the expansion of the United States in the early
nineteenth century to trace U.S. growth and form hypotheses
about future conflicts.

2471BE31400E4E5182385F720D23ED32.description:
Infer how events of this period led to the development of
philosophies, interest groups and political parties.

6E6B0C38EBD444DDAF34D91BE8ACE5F2.description:
Evaluate the responses of early American leaders to the
social, political, economic and religious challenges facing
the new nation.

68087DB6BCB546DC951EA4476CF76C6E.description:
Explain the major debates that occurred during the adoption of
the Constitution and their ultimate resolution.

82D0543CD24142BDB8616C525838A383.description:
Evaluate the strengths and weaknesses of the American
colonies and Great Britain to explain the American victory in
the Revolution.

A3CC3018261240B0957AD0F03EA48A4D.description:
Analyze the Declaration of Independence to determine the
historical context and political philosophies that influenced its
creation.

85DDF59950204552BE340C6856CDDECA.description:
Trace the events leading to escalating conflict between
Great Britainand the colonies, from multiple viewpoints.

B5CB7204E2B74E38ADB42A79849DE18E.description:
Analyze the concept of Manifest Destiny as a catalyst for
change in American history.

26C20F0A41DE4974A97063561579580C.description:
Describe the causes and consequences of the Seven Years
War as a turning point in American history.

33F65B8DD0ED4AD69E5F8F0EE5F5AD4A.description:
Trace the causes and consequences of conflict and
cooperation between Native Americans and North and South
American colonists using multiple viewpoints.

052E27DDCC47402F8AE89C6196F2C165.description:
Comparemotivating factors leading Europeans to settle in the
New World to explain colonial diversity and regionaldifferences
in North and South America.

8427807D02B840149F3D9C458E2794E8.description:
Trace the causes and consequences of indigenous peoples
arriving in the Americas beginning c. 15,000 BCE.

7C604E5D5ECD45828516E2ABD2E44485.description:
Analyze the causes and consequences of a specific problem in
American history prior to c. 1870 as well as the challenges and
opportunities faced by those trying to address the problem.

1667E47608204780BCA3351F4D43C22D.description:
Using an inquiry lens, develop compelling questions about
American history prior to 1870, to determine helpful resources
and consider multiple points of views represented in the
resources.

BE5F5A59D364457887390162B1C4C675.description:
With assistance, develop a research plan, identify appropriate
resources for investigating social studies’ topics and create a
research product which applies an aspect of American history
prior to c. 1870 to a contemporary issue.

D1F430ED49194C66BA676540BA67A27C.description:
Explain connections between historical context and peoples’
perspectives at the time in American history.

F1EB14C34E0F488386376C9569AB92BA.description:
Create and use tools to analyze a chronological sequence of
related events in American history.
